'''Asfar ibn Shiruya''' ([[Gilaki language|Gilaki]]/{{lang-fa|اسفار بن شیرویه}}: died 931) was an Iranian military leader of [[Gilaks|Gilaki]] origin, active in northern [[Iran]] (esp. [[Tabaristan]] and [[Jibal]]) in the early 10th century. He played a major role in the succession disputes of the [[Alid dynasties of northern Iran|Alids of Tabaristan]], and managed to establish himself as the ruler of Tabaristan and northern Jibal briefly from 928 to 930.

==Name==
''Asfār'' is a local [[Caspian languages|Caspian]] form of [[Middle Persian]] ''aswār'', which means "rider, cavalryman". The [[New Persian]] form of the word is ''savār''.{{sfn|Bosworth|1987|pp=747-748}}

== Biography ==
===Background and early life===
[[File:Caspian coast of Iran during the Iranian intermezzo.png|thumb|right|300px|Map of northern Iran]]
A native of [[Lahijan]], Asfar belonged to the Gilaki clan of Varudavand{{cref|b}}, and was the son of a certain Shiruya (Sheroe).{{sfn|Bosworth|1987|pp=747-748}} Asfar had a brother named Shirzad, and grew up in an environment where "[[Culture of Iran|Iranian culture]], memories of the glories of the [[Sasanian Empire|Persian Empire]], were alive among them." Like many other Gilakis and Daylamites, Asfar was not a Muslim—he was in fact a nationalist, who admired the Persian Empire.{{sfn|Bosworth|1987|pp=747-748}} According to the 10th-century [[Arabs|Arab]] historian [[al-Masudi]], most of the [[Daylamites|Daylamite]] and Gilaki leaders, who were [[Zoroastrianism|Zoroastrian]] and pagan, had become [[atheist]]s.{{sfn|Madelung|1969|p=88}} Asfar was one of the many Gilaki leaders that entered into the service of the [[Alid dynasties of northern Iran|Alids]], after establishing their rule over [[Tabaristan]], [[Gilan Province|Gilan]], and [[Daylam]].{{sfn|Madelung|1969|p=88}}

===Rise to power===
Asfar is first mentioned in 917, during the succession disputes for control in Tabaristan after the death of the Alid ruler [[Hasan al-Utrush]] (r. 914–917). Eventually, [[Hasan ibn Qasam]] (called ''al-da'i al-saghir'', "the lesser missionary") managed to emerge victorious. It was around this period, that the [[Samanid Empire]] was seeking to expand their power from [[Transoxiana]] and [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]] into northern Iran, opposing [[Zaidiyyah|Zaydi Shia Islam]] there whilst advocating the Sunni movement against it.{{sfn|Bosworth|1987|pp=747-748}}

===Reign and downfall===
Asfar now expanded his domains over [[Rey, Iran|Ray]], [[Qazvin]] and other parts of [[Jibal]], initially apparently as a delegate of the Samanids, but thereafter as an sovereign ruler, assuming the emblem of kingship at Ray in disregard of Nasr II and the [[Abbasid Caliphate|Abbasid]] [[caliph]], [[al-Muqtadir]] (r. 908-932). He reportedly killed a great number of the citizens of Qazvin, burned the markets, demolished mosques and killed the ''[[muezzin]]'', and prohibited the ''[[salah]]''. Furthermore, he enforced a poll-tax on the whole population of the city, along with traders visiting from other countries, thus acquiring a vast sum.{{sfn|Bosworth|1987|pp=747-748}} He also appointed his lieutenant and compatriot [[Mardavij]] as the governor of [[Zanjan, Iran|Zanjan]]. 
[[File:Iran - Qazvin - Alamout Castle View.jpg|thumb|260px|View of the [[Alamut Castle]], where Asfar had left his vast treasure.]]
In 930, Mardavij along with Asfar's brother, Shirzad, were ordered to capture [[Tarom County|Tarom]], the capital of the [[Sallarid dynasty|Sallarid]] ruler [[Muhammad ibn Musafir]]. During the siege, Mardavij, on the urging of Makan and Muhammad, betrayed Asfar by revolting against him. With the aid of Muhammad and Makan, Mardavij defeated and killed Shirzad, including other members of the Varudavand clan. He then marched towards Qazvin, the residence of Asfar. However, Asfar managed to flee. Mardavij thus founded the [[Ziyarid dynasty]], and became ruler of Asfar's former territories.{{sfn|Madelung|1975|p=212}}

Asfar was chased into Khorasan, being left no choice but to leave the treasure which he had assembled in the [[Alamut Castle|castle]] of [[Alamut]] in Daylam. When Asfar arrived at [[Sabzevar|Bayhaq]], however, he went back, aiming to recover his treasure at Alamut. But when he entered Talaqan, a town in Daylam near Qazvin,{{sfn|Pellat|Cahen|2012}} he was overwhelmed and killed by Mardavij, most likely in 931.{{sfn|Bosworth|1987|pp=747-748}}

