[[Air Chief Marshal]] '''Sir Charles Stuart Burnett''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KCB|CBE|DSO}} (3 April 1882 – 9 April 1945) was a senior commander in the [[Royal Air Force]] during the first half of the 20th century. He was Air Officer Commanding [[RAF Iraq Command|Iraq Command]] during the early 1930s. During the [[Second World War]], he served as [[Chief of Air Force (Australia)|Chief of the Air Staff]] of the [[Royal Australian Air Force]].

==Early life==
Charles Burnett was born in [[Browns Valley, Minnesota]], United States on 3 April 1882. He was the second son of John Alexander Burnett and Charlotte Susan Burnett. John Burnett was originally from the Scottish village of [[Kemnay]] in [[Aberdeenshire]].<ref name="ODNB">{{cite web | last =Jordan | first =David | title =Burnett, Sir Charles Stuart | work =Oxford Dictionary of National Biography | url =http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/32188 | accessdate = 2007-11-03}}
</ref>

Burnett was educated at [[Bedford School]] in England. His younger brother was [[Robert Burnett]] who was later knighted and rose to the rank of [[Admiral (Royal Navy)|admiral]].<ref name="ODNB"/>

==Early career==
In 1899, Burnett enlisted as a private in the [[Imperial Yeomanry]] in order to fight in the [[Second Boer War]]. Burnett claimed to be 18 when he was in fact only 17.<ref name="ODNB"/> He was discharged in 1901 in order that he might take a [[Commissioned officer|commission]] and he was [[London Gazette|gazetted]] as a [[second lieutenant]] in the [[Highland Light Infantry]] in October 1901.<ref name="air_of_auth">{{cite web | last =Barrass | first =Malcolm | title =Air Chief Marshal Sir Charles Burnett | work =Air of Authority – A History of RAF Organisation | url =http://www.rafweb.org/Biographies/Burnett_C.htm | accessdate = 2007-11-03}}
</ref> Burnett was then attached to the Imperial Yeomanry for the next three years.<ref name="air_of_auth"/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27434|page=3253|date=16 May 1902}}</ref> He temporarily held the rank of lieutenant from 26 April 1902<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27432|page=3091|date=9 May 1902}}</ref> to 7 February 1903.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27523|pages=844–847|date=10 February 1903}}</ref>

On 20 August 1904, Burnett was seconded to the [[West African Frontier Force]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27712|page=5843|date=9 September 1904}}</ref> During the next five years Burnett saw action in [[Northern Nigeria]], contracted [[blackwater fever]], was promoted to [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] and was twice [[mentioned in despatches]].<ref name="ODNB"/><ref name="air_of_auth"/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28036|page=4518|date=2 July 1907}}</ref>

Burnett resigned his commission in September 1909<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=28301|page=7851|date=26 October 1909}}</ref> and then entered business as a part-owner of a shop in [[Portuguese Guinea]].<ref name="ADB">{{cite web | last =O'Neill | first =Robert | title =Burnett, Sir Charles Stuart | work =Australian Dictionary of Biography | url =http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A130350b.htm | accessdate = 2007-11-03}}
</ref> He did not meet with particular success as a businessman and by 1911 was employed by the British diplomatic service as the assistant [[Resident (title)|resident]] in [[Ilorin]], Nigeria.<ref name="ODNB"/><ref name="ADB"/>

==First World War==
With the outbreak of hostilities in 1914, Burnett rejoined the [[British Army]]. After [[List of pilots awarded an Aviator's Certificate by the Royal Aero Club in 1914|qualifying as a pilot in November 1914]],<ref>Burnett was awarded Aviator's Certificate no. 985 on 24 November 1914</ref> he was commissioned as a lieutenant on 4 December 1914.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=29042|supp=y|page=582|date=15 January 1915}}</ref> Burnett married Sybil Pack-Beresford just six days before his first posting as a [[Royal Flying Corps]] wing adjutant, which brought a temporary promotion to [[Captain (British Army and Royal Marines)|captain]].<ref name="ODNB"/><ref name="air_of_auth"/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=29014|supp=y|page=10904|date=18 December 1914}}</ref> In May 1915, Burnett was posted as a flight commander on [[No. XVII Squadron RAF|No. 17 Squadron]] where he flew [[Royal Aircraft Factory B.E.2|BE2c]] from [[Gosport]] and then Egypt.<ref name="air_of_auth"/> He became a substantive captain on 1 October 1916.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=29444|supp=y|page=831|date=18 January 1916}}</ref>

On 2 April 1916, Burnett was promoted to temporary [[Major (United Kingdom)|major]] and appointed Officer Commanding of [[No. 36 Squadron RAF|No. 36 Squadron]], which was stationed in [[Cramlington]]. In October the same year Burnett was sent to the Western Front as Officer Commanding [[No. 12 Squadron RAF|No. 12 Squadron]]. During his tour as Officer Commanding No. 12 Squadron, Burnett was once again mentioned in despatches.<ref name="air_of_auth"/>

With a promotion to temporary lieutenant colonel on 8 October 1917,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30354|supp=y|page=11092|date=26 October 1917}}</ref> Burnett was granted command of the Flying Corps' [[Fifth Wing RFC|Fifth Wing]]<ref name="air_of_auth"/> which was operating in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]]. Following his wing's contribution to the British victory in the [[Battle of Jerusalem (1917)|Battle of Jerusalem]] in December 1917, Burnett was awarded the [[Distinguished Service Order]].<ref name="ODNB"/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=30624|supp=y|page=4410|date=9 April 1918}}</ref> He was also awarded the Egyptian [[Order of the Nile]], Third Class,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31647|supp=y|page=14002|date=18 November 1919}}</ref> and in the 1919 [[King's Birthday Honours]] he was made a [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in recognition of his wartime service in Egypt.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31378|supp=y|page=7026|date=30 May 1919}}</ref>

==Inter-war period==
By the close of the war, Burnett had transferred to the newly formed [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF) and the next few years of his military career were to involve many changes of post. In 1919, Burnett was promoted to the temporary rank of [[Brigadier general (United Kingdom)|brigadier general]]<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=31486|page=9871|date=1 August 1919}}</ref> and appointed (again temporarily) as [[General Officer Commanding]] the RAF's [[RAF Palestine Brigade|Palestine Brigade]]. Later the same year, he accepted the offer of a permanent commission in the RAF with the rank of [[Wing commander (rank)|wing commander]].

In April 1920, Burnett was given command of the RAF's [[Mesopotamian Wing RAF|Mesopotamian Wing]] and when the wing was upgraded to a [[group (air force)|group]], he worked as a [[staff officer]] at the group's HQ. From February to October 1921, Burnett was a [[wikt:supernumerary|supernumerary]], first at the HQ Middle East Area and then at [[No. 7 Group RAF|No. 7 Group]] where he was sent pending his next posting. It was during this time that Burnett was promoted to [[group captain]], although for some of the period he was on the half-pay list.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=32391|page=5646|date=15 July 1921}}</ref>

Burnett took up command of [[No. 29 Group RAF|No. 29 Group]] in October 1921 but this was a short-lived appointment. In April 1922, Burnett was posted as station commander of [[RAF Leuchars]] which was a training base at that time. Once again Burnett did not spend long in post. By December 1922, he was a supernumerary once more, this time at the RAF Depot.<ref name="air_of_auth"/> From 1923-early 1927, Burnett served as the Deputy Director of Operations and Intelligence<ref name="air_of_auth"/> at the Air Ministry.<ref name="ODNB"/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=32803|page=1823|date=6 March 1923}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33243|page=584|date=28 January 1927}}</ref>  He was made a [[Companion of the Bath]] (CB) in the [[1927 New Year Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33235|supp=y|page=3|date=31 December 1926}}</ref> Burnett was then posted as the [[Commandant]] of the [[Central Flying School]] where he served until January 1929.<ref name="air_of_auth"/>

Having just been promoted to [[air commodore]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33453|page=71|date=1 January 1929}}</ref> Burnett's next tour saw him return to Iraq as the Senior Air Staff Officer at the HQ of [[RAF Iraq Command|Iraq Command]] where he served for the next two years. In early 1931, he returned to the United Kingdom and he was appointed to the double-hatted position of [[Deputy Chief of the Air Staff]] and Director of Operations and Intelligence.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33688|page=932|date=10 February 1931}}</ref>  Burnett was promoted [[air vice-marshal]] the following July and he remained in post for a little under a year and a half.<ref name="air_of_auth"/><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33731|page=4250|date=30 June 1931}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=33913|supp=y|page=1180|date=21 February 1933}}</ref>

In November 1932, Burnett returned to Iraq once more, this time as the [[Air Officer Commanding]] [[RAF Iraq Command|Iraq Command]] which placed him in charge of all British forces in Iraq. During his time in command Burnett was involved in the suppression of several tribal incursions near [[Kuwait]] and during one such occasion Burnett was wounded.<ref name="ODNB"/>

Burnett returned to Great Britain at the start of 1935 to take up command of the RAF's [[RAF Inland Area|Inland Area]]. At the start of 1936, whilst Burnett was Air Officer Commanding Inland Area, he was promoted to [[air marshal]]<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34237|page=8407|date=31 December 1935}}</ref> and made a [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath]] (KCB) in the New Year Honours list.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34238|supp=y|page=4|date=31 December 1935}}</ref> Later that year the RAF's [[Command (military formation)|command]] structure underwent a major reorganization. One of the changes was the redesignation of Inland Area as [[RAF Training Command|Training Command]] and Burnett became the command's first [[Air Officer Commanding-in-Chief]]. The next three years placed great demands upon Burnett and his command; as the threat from the German ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' increased, Training Command played a key role in the expansion of the RAF.<ref name="air_of_auth"/><ref name="ADB"/>

In July 1939, just prior to the outbreak of the [[Second World War]], Burnett was appointed an additional [[Inspector-General of the RAF]]<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34641|supp=y|page=4452|date=30 June 1939}}</ref> and in August he was a member of British military mission to the [[Soviet Union]].<ref name="ADB"/>

==Second World War==
===RAAF Chief of the Air Staff===
Burnett continued in his role as Inspector-General of the RAF until 1940 when he was appointed [[Chief of Air Force (Australia)|Chief of the Air Staff]] of the [[Royal Australian Air Force]]. Burnett's appointment to the senior post in the RAAF was not without controversy. Apart from the fact that by 1940 Burnett was due for retirement and his health was not at its best, the choice of a British officer over an Australian one caused open resentment in many quarters of the RAAF.<ref name="ODNB"/> The Australian prime minister, [[Robert Menzies]], had decided that a British officer should head the RAAF, believing that Australian officers lacked the necessary experience.<ref name="ODNB"/><ref>Odgers, ''The Royal Australian Air Force'', p.60</ref> After discussions between the British and Australian governments, Burnett was selected and given an acting promotion to [[air chief marshal]],<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=34778|supp=y|page=464|date=23 January 1940}}</ref> a rank he subsequently retained.<ref name="ODNB"/>

The vexed question of Australia's role in the [[British Commonwealth Air Training Plan|Empire Air Training Scheme]] (EATS) had led to the resignation of Air Vice-Marshal [[Stanley Goble]], the previous substantive RAAF Chief of the Air Staff. Unlike Goble and several other senior RAAF commanders, Burnett believed that his most important task was to implement EATS to the full and thereby increase Australia's ability to provide aircrew to the RAF.<ref name="ODNB"/> Under Burnett the RAAF expanded from a strength of 3,489 men just prior to the outbreak of war to 79,074 in May 1942. Of the approximately 80,000 personnel in the RAAF when Burnett was replaced, 42 per cent were EATS personnel.<ref name="ADB"/>

Burnett also strove to increase the number of aircraft in the RAAF, although in this regard he was less successful than he was with increasing aircrew numbers. Under Burnett, RAAF units were placed in forward positions and priority was given to the aerial protection of Australian sea lanes.<ref name="ADB"/> He also took a key role in the establishments of the [[Women's Auxiliary Australian Air Force]] (WAAAF) and RAAF health services, the latter having previously been provided by the [[Australian Army]].<ref>Helson, ''"10 Years at the Top"'', p.42</ref>

===Return to United Kingdom and death===
[[File:Jones-Bostock-Burnett AWM 012249.jpg|thumb|right|Burnett (right) with his replacement as RAAF [[Chief of Air Force (Australia)|CAS]], [[Air vice marshal|AVM]] George Jones (left), and AVM William Bostock (centre), May 1942]]
From October 1941, Burnett had a strained working relationship with [[Arthur Drakeford]], the [[Australian Labor Party]]'s minister for air who had just then been appointed. Burnett and Drakeford frequently clashed and when in early 1942 Burnett proposed sweeping organizational changes, including the abolition of the [[Air Board (Australia)|Australian Air Board]], a breaking point was reached.  It had also been widely argued that Burnett's focus on the European theatre resulted in the RAAF lacking sufficient defensive strength and by 1942 the threat of invasion by Japan was growing. Burnett was replaced in May 1942 by an Australian, Air Vice Marshal [[George Jones (RAAF officer)|George Jones]], who succeeded to the position despite Burnett's lobbying for his deputy, Air Vice Marshal [[William Bostock]], to take over.<ref name="ODNB"/><ref name="ADB"/><ref>Stephens, ''The Royal Australian Air Force'', pp.116–119</ref>

Burnett retired from the RAF shortly after his return to Britain, but in 1943 he worked full-time in the RAF's cadet organisation, the [[Air Training Corps]], as the commandant of the ATC's Central Command. In this role, Burnett was responsible for ATC squadrons in Hertfordshire, Middlesex, Buckinghamshire, Oxfordshire, Berkshire and Bedfordshire.<ref>http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1943/1943%20-%200025.html</ref><ref>http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1943/1943%20-%200426.html</ref>  By 1945 Burnett remained as commandant<ref>http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1945/1945%20-%200747.html</ref> but his health was declining and on 9 April 1945 he died of a coronary [[thrombosis]] at the Princess Mary Hospital at [[RAF Halton]]. Charles Burnett was survived by his wife and four daughters.<ref name="ODNB"/>

